# Diary ‚Äî <work item name>

> Spec: [`spec.md`](./spec.md) ‚Ä¢ Progress: [`progress.md`](./progress.md)
> Started: <YYYY-MM-DD>

Chronological narrative of this work item: discoveries, decisions, plan changes, surprises, dead
ends, and resolutions. Append-only ‚Äî new entries go at the **top** (newest first). Old entries are
not deleted or rewritten; if you're wrong about something, write a new entry correcting it.

> **Reading discipline (keeps reviews and handoffs cheap).** This file grows without bound. Agents
> read the **recent slice** ‚Äî entries since the last review, or the last ~10 ‚Äî not the whole history;
> they reach for older entries only when a specific finding needs the backstory. So keep each entry
> short (one paragraph) and self-contained, and capture the *why*, not a diff dump.
>
> **Optional compaction.** When the diary grows past ~40 entries on a long-running work item, a human
> (or an explicit request) may fold resolved, no-longer-relevant entries into a single dated
> **"Compacted: <range>"** summary entry, preserving every decision-change, blocker, and supersession
> verbatim. Never compact silently and never drop a `decision-change` / `plan-change` entry ‚Äî those
> are the audit trail.

**Always write a diary entry when**:

- A decision in `decisions.md` changes (supersession).
- A phase or iteration shape changes (scope, files touched, acceptance).
- An assumption from `context.md` turns out to be wrong.
- A blocker is hit, and again when it's resolved.
- A review surfaces a finding that affects the plan (not just the code).
- A discovery during coding shifts the spec.

Each entry is short ‚Äî one paragraph, plain language. Pretend you're writing to a teammate who'll
read this in three months and needs to understand "what happened on this work item."

